720186f-a.text:
113-123 Greenwich Street (foreground), adjoining the S.E. corner of Thames Street, showing the site where the New York Curb Exchange will stand. Also seen is a portion of the Sixth Ave. Elevated Line on Trinity Place, and across same, the Trinity grave yard. Buildings facing on the east side of
Broadway appear in the background.
About 1921.
Gift of E. M. Jenks.

720187f-d.text:
Greenwich Street, west side, north from Albany Street, showing at the N.W. corner a 37 -story building formerly known as the Planters Hotel. This building No. 122 Greenwich Street, was for a time a dry,goods store; patronised by Henry Clay and other celebrites. Overhead, on
Greenwich Street, is the Ninth Ave. Elevated Line.
May 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same.
May 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(3)
A view eastward on Albany Street, and showing the side of the former Planters Hotel. From that point, to the immediate foreground appear; No. 3 (2-story structure); Nos. 5 and 7; all on Albany Street. Across Greenwich Street, appears the Hamilton Building, No. 125-131 Greenwich
Street, at the S.E. corner of Thames Street.
May 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(4) The sam,at a lnter nete.
